{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かね}}

Appears to be a fusion of ''kana'' + {{der|ja|ojp|-|sort=かね}} emphatic nominal particle {{ja-l|い||i}}. Compare the development of modern ''kami'' from ''kamu'' + ''i'' at {{ja-l|神}}, ''te'' from ''ta'' + ''i'' at {{ja-l|手}}, ''me'' from ''ma'' + ''i'' at {{ja-l|目}}, ''kaze'' from ''kaza'' + ''i'' at {{ja-l|風}}.

{{IPAchar|/kana/}} + {{IPAchar|/i/}} → {{IPAchar|/*kanai/}} → {{IPAchar|/kane/}}

The four kanji spellings of this term, {{lang|ja|金}} (“gold”), {{m|ja|銀||silver}}, {{m|ja|銅||copper}}, and {{m|ja|鉄||iron}}, hint at the importance of each of these four metals in ancient Japan.

{{ja-noun|かね}}

# [[money]]
#: ⇒ {{ja-l|お金||okane}}
# [[metal]]

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|こがね}}
{{IPAchar|/kuɡane/}} → {{IPAchar|/koɡane/}}

Alteration of ''kugane''<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>, possibly influenced by metaphor from {{m|ja|小金|tr=kogane||a small amount of money}}, or by the {{ll|ja|漢音|''kan'on''}} reading of ''kō'' for the {{ja-l|黄}} character.

{{ja-noun|こがね}}

